In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims January 2015 as National Mentoring Month. He emphasizes the importance of providing support and opportunities for young Americans to unlock their potential. Mentors and caring adults play a vital role in inspiring and uplifting young people, helping them build a better future for themselves and the country. The Obama Administration is working to expand mentoring opportunities, increase apprenticeship programs, connect underrepresented groups with role models in STEM fields, and encourage college students to mentor high schoolers. The First Lady and President Obama have started mentoring initiatives at the White House, pairing local students with professionals. The President calls upon public officials, business and community leaders, educators, and Americans nationwide to observe National Mentoring Month with appropriate ceremonies, activities, and programs.